#  DNS Reconnaissance

---

## Overview

DNS Reconnaissance is the process of identifying records associated with a target domain. The goal is to map out the infrastructure of a target by uncovering:

-  Mail server addresses (MX records)
-  IP addresses (A / AAAA records)
-  Name server addresses (NS records)
-  TXT records and other metadata

> [!info] Context This falls under **Passive Reconnaissance** — we are gathering publicly available information without directly interacting with the target's systems.

---

## Tools

### 1. DNSRecon

> A command-line tool used for DNS reconnaissance, enumeration, and information gathering. Designed for security professionals and ethical hackers to assess network security and identify potential vulnerabilities.



![host command output](image2.png)

#### Basic Usage

```bash
dnsrecon -d example.com
```

#### What It Returns

|Record Type|Description|
|---|---|
|`NS`|Name server addresses|
|`A`|IPv4 address of the domain|
|`AAAA`|IPv6 address of the domain|
|`MX`|Mail server address|
|`TXT`|SPF, DKIM, and other text records|

> [!warning] Note on IP Addresses Highly technical servers (e.g., **Cloudflare**) may mask the actual origin IP. The address returned may belong to a proxy/CDN rather than the real server.

#### Common Flags

```bash
dnsrecon -d example.com          # Standard enumeration
dnsrecon -d example.com -t std   # Standard record lookup
dnsrecon -d example.com -t brt   # Brute-force subdomains
```

---

### 2. DNS Dumpster

> **Site:** [dnsdumpster.com](https://dnsdumpster.com/)

A free, web-based domain research tool that discovers hosts related to a domain. It provides the same data as DNSRecon but in an **organized, visual format**.

#### Key Features

-  Sorted and structured DNS record output
-  **Graphical network chart** visualizing host relationships
-  Attacker's-perspective view of visible hosts
- No installation required — browser-based

#### Why It Matters

> Finding visible hosts from the attacker's perspective is a critical part of the security assessment process.

